data.enText: to be typical of a person, place or thing

data.chText: 成为英格兰这一地区特征的绵延起伏的丘陵地
data.enText: the rolling hills that characterize this part of England

data.chText: 使…具有特点（或最引人注目的特征）
data.enText: to give sth its typical or most noticeable qualities or features

data.chText: 这座城市的特点是钢铁和玻璃建造的现代化高楼大厦林立。
data.enText: The city is characterized by tall modern buildings in steel and glass.

data.chText: 描述，刻画，表现（…的特征、特点）
data.enText: to describe or show the qualities of sb/sth in a particular way

data.chText: 被描述为“男性”或“女性”工作的各种活动
data.enText: activities that are characterized as ‘male’ or ‘female’ work

means: 使…具有特点(或最引人注目的特征)

tr: describe or portray the character or the qualities or peculiarities of
example: You can characterize his behavior as that of an egotist
This poem can be characterized as a lament for a dead lover

value.boxr_value: in BRIT, also use 英国英语亦用 characterise

value.def: If something is characterized by a particular feature or quality, that feature or quality is an obvious part of it.

example.ex: This election campaign has been characterized by violence...
example.tran: 暴力行为已成为这次竞选活动的一大特点。

example.ex: A bold use of colour characterizes the bedroom.
example.tran: 这间卧室的特点是用色大胆。

value.def: If you characterize someone or something as a particular thing, you describe them as that thing.

example.ex: Both companies have characterized the relationship as friendly...
example.tran: 两家公司都认为彼此之间关系友好。

example.ex: This play is characterized as a comedy.
I don't fully agree with that characterization of the welfare system.
example.tran: 我并不完全同意对福利制度的描述。
